Background & terminology

Genetic epidemiology

  • Explore the role of genetic factors in health and disease in families and populations
  • General methods
    • Segregation analyses
    • Linkage studies
    • Genetic risk studies
    • Association studies

Genetic association studies

  • Aim
    • Assess whether genetic information is related to a disease or some measure of disease progression
  • Study population & design
    • Typically unrelated individuals
    • Common epidemiologic designs (case-control, cohort)
  • Common observational studies
    • Candidate gene study
    • Genome-wide association study (GWAS)

Quick intro to genetics

  • DNA is the carrier of genetic information within a cell
  • Consists of two chains wrapped around each other that twist to form a double helix
  • Each chain is made up of repeating subunits, called nucleotides, which are the building blocks for DNA
  • Four types of bases: adenine (A), thymine (T), guanine (G), and cytosine (C)

Quick intro to genetics

Gene

  • One particular section of DNA that encodes for a specific function
  • Genes affect our observable characteristics or traits
  • Genes can acquire mutations in their sequence, leading to different variants

Markers of genetic variation

Single-nucleotide polymorphism (SNP)

  • Genetic marker often used in association studies
  • Most common type of genetic variant in humans
  • Each SNP represents a change in a single nucleotide
  • Typically two possible nucleotide variations (ex. A or G), which are called alleles

Genetic differences

  • For a SNP, each person has two bases (one inherited from each parent)

Genotype

  • A person's genetic makeup, a gene or set of genes carried by an individual
  • Genotypes can be homozygous (same base pairs, ex. AA or GG) or heterozygous (more than one allele, ex. AG)

Data cleaning

  • Methods for collecting data on genotype can lead to errors
  • Quality control (QC) measures for SNPs
    • Minor allele frequency
    • Call rate (missingness)
    • Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium

QC measures for SNPs

Minor allele frequency (MAF)

  • Frequency of the less common allele in a population
  • Common to exclude SNPs with MAF below 1-2%

QC measures for SNPs

Call rate

  • Proportion of individuals where the SNP information is not missing
  • Good indicator of marker quality (high missingness suggests poor measurement)
  • Typically remove SNPs with a call rate below 95-99%

QC measures for SNPs

Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium (HWE)

  • In the absence of other factors, allele and genotype frequencies in a population will remain constant from generation to generation
  • Two common tests
    • Chi-Square test
    • Exact test
  • Threshold for significance typically set to 10-3 to 10-6

Using R for genetic association studies

R packages

  • Tons of R packages available for performing genetic analyses
  • Some especially useful ones for genetic association studies
    • genetics
    • GenABEL
    • SNPassoc
    • Poppr
    • pegas
    • LDheatmap
    • popgen
    • gap
    • qqman

Bioconductor

  • Provides tools for the analysis and comprehension of high-throughput genomic data
  • Started in 2001 and run by the Bioconductor team based primarily at the Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center
  • Several R packages available for analyzing SNP data

Association study analysis

  • Basic approach
    • Obtain data on genetic and disease information
    • Examine quality control (QC) statistics
    • Code genetic information according to a specific disease model
    • Test association (ex. GLM)

SNP QC

Hardy-Weinberg equilibrium (HWE)

  • Null hypothesis: HWE holds

Exact test

snp.hwe.e = HWE.exact(genotype(data$rs10))
snp.hwe.e$p.value
## [1] 0.7897327

Chi-Square Test

snp.hwe.c = HWE.chisq(genotype(data$rs10))
snp.hwe.c$p.value
## [1] 0.7991201

SNP QC

Checking MAF, call rate, & HWE for a large number of SNPs

check.snp = function(SNP){
  snp.summ = summary(genotype(SNP))
  snp.info = c(snp.summ$allele.freq[,2][2], 
               snp.summ$n.typed / snp.summ$n.total,
               HWE.exact(genotype(SNP))$p.value)
  names(snp.info) = c("maf", "call.rate", "hwe.exact.p")
  return(snp.info)
}

check.snp(data$rs10)
##         maf   call.rate hwe.exact.p 
##   0.1325503   0.9536000   0.7897327

SNP QC

Exclude SNPs that did not pass QC checks

snps.exl = c(rownames(snp.qc[which(snp.qc$call.rate<0.95),]),
             rownames(snp.qc[which(snp.qc$maf<0.05),]),
             rownames(snp.qc[which(snp.qc$hwe.exact.p<0.001),]))
snps.exl = snps.exl[!duplicated(snps.exl)]

data.qc = subset(data, select = -which(colnames(data) %in% snps.exl))

Association between SNP & outcome

Logistic regression model for a single SNP

mod = glm(case.ctrl ~ dominant(genotype(rs10)), 
          family=binomial(link = "logit"), data=data)

Create vector of results

mod.info = c(exp(c(mod$coef[2], 
                   confint(mod)[2,])), 
             car::Anova(mod, type="III")$"Pr(>Chisq)")
names(mod.info) = c("OR", "L", "U", "p")
mod.info
##        OR         L         U         p 
## 0.8112304 0.4279456 1.5181397 0.5128583

Association between SNP & outcome

Logistic regression models for multiple SNPs

mod.snp = function(SNP, DATA){
  mod = glm(case.ctrl ~ dominant(genotype(SNP)), 
            family=binomial(link = "logit"), data=DATA)
  mod.info = c(exp(c(mod$coef[2], confint(mod)[2,])), 
               car::Anova(mod, type="III")$"Pr(>Chisq)")
  names(mod.info) = c("OR", "L", "U", "p")
  return(mod.info)
}

mod.snp(data.qc$rs10, data.qc)
##        OR         L         U         p 
## 0.8112304 0.4279456 1.5181397 0.5128583

Association between SNP & outcome

Logistic regression models for multiple SNPs

GWAS association

Logistic regression models for GWAS data

GenABEL package

qtscore(case.ctrl~gender+age, data, trait.type="binomial",
        snps=c(1:100000))

GWASTools package

source("https://bioconductor.org/biocLite.R")
biocLite("GWASTools")

assocRegression(data, outcome="case.ctrl", model.type="logistic",
                covar=c("gender", "age"), snpStart=1, snpEnd=100000)

bonf.p = p.adjust(mod.results[,4], method = "bonferroni")

Visualizing results

Forest plot

ggplot(mod.results, aes(y=OR, x = reorder(rownames(mod.results), OR))) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=L, ymax=U), width=.2) +
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, linetype=2, color="red") +
  coord_flip() +
  labs(title = "", x = "SNP", y = "OR") +
  theme_bw() + 
  theme(axis.text.y=element_text(size=6))

Visualizing results

Visualizing results

P-value vs. SNP position

data.lz = merge(mod.results, data.snp.info, by="row.names", all.x=T)
data.lz$p.trans = -log10(data.lz$p) 

ggplot(data.lz, aes(y=p.trans, x = Position)) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_hline(yintercept = -log10(0.05), linetype=3, color="grey") +
  geom_text(data=subset(data.lz, p < 0.05),
            aes(Position, p.trans, label=Row.names), 
            hjust=-0.15 , color="red") +
  geom_point(data=subset(data.lz, p < 0.05),
             aes(Position, p.trans), color="red") +
  labs(title = "", x = "Position", y = "-log10(p)") +
  theme_bw()
